00:00:00.534 --> 00:00:01.950
What I want to do
in this video is

00:00:01.950 --> 00:00:10.800
think about the difference
between a line segment, a line,

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:13.210
and a ray.

00:00:13.210 --> 00:00:18.780
And this is the pure geometrical
versions of these things.

00:00:18.780 --> 00:00:20.640
And so, a line segment
is actually probably

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:23.950
what most of us associate with
a line in our everyday lives.

00:00:23.950 --> 00:00:27.210
A line segment is
something just like that.

00:00:27.210 --> 00:00:29.560
For lack of a better
word, a straight line.

00:00:29.560 --> 00:00:32.330
But why we call it a
segment is that it actually

00:00:32.330 --> 00:00:34.300
has a starting and
a stopping point.

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:36.210
So, most of the lines
that we experience

00:00:36.210 --> 00:00:38.590
in our everyday
reality are actually

00:00:38.590 --> 00:00:40.240
line segments when
we think of it

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:42.242
from a pure geometrical
point of view.

00:00:42.242 --> 00:00:44.200
and I know I drew a little
bit of a curve here,

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:46.570
but this is supposed to
be completely straight,

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:47.950
but this is a line segment.

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:50.870
The segment is based
on the fact that it

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:52.770
has an ending point
and a starting point,

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:54.630
or a starting point
and an ending point.

00:00:54.630 --> 00:00:56.380
A line, if you're
thinking about it

00:00:56.380 --> 00:01:01.370
in the pure geometric sense
of a line, is essentially,

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:02.412
it does not stop.

00:01:02.412 --> 00:01:04.620
It doesn't have a starting
point and an ending point.

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:08.230
It keeps going on forever
in both directions.

00:01:08.230 --> 00:01:09.735
So a line would look like this.

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:15.110
And to show that it
keeps on going on

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:18.610
forever in that direction right
over there, we draw this arrow,

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:20.980
and to keep showing
that it goes on forever

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:22.620
in kind of the down
left direction,

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:25.040
we draw this arrow
right over here.

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:28.090
So obviously, I've never
encountered something

00:01:28.090 --> 00:01:31.530
that just keeps on
going straight forever.

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:33.530
But in math-- that's the
neat thing about math--

00:01:33.530 --> 00:01:35.620
we can think about
these abstract notions.

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:39.660
And so the mathematical purest
geometric sense of a line

00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:43.100
is this straight thing
that goes on forever.

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:45.000
Now, a ray is
something in between.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.070
A ray has a well
defined starting point.

00:01:48.070 --> 00:01:50.140
So that's its starting
point, but then

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:52.580
it just keeps on
going on forever.

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:55.650
So the ray might
start over here,

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:59.760
but then it just keeps on going.

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:02.195
So that right over
there is a ray.

